research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:19:    "hypothesis": "\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4fdd\u6301\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_e \u03a3_{i\u2208S_e(x)} \u03b1_{e,i}(x) b_{e,i}\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d e(x) \u7531\u8f7b\u91cf router \u9009\u51fa\u7684\u5355\u4e2a expert\uff0c{B_e} \u662f\u9759\u6001 expert \u5b50\u5e93\u3002\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u5728\u7ebf\u94fe\u8def\u4ecd\u662f\u201crouter \u9009\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5b50\u5e93 -> \u5b50\u5e93\u5185 local top-k -> \u67e5\u8868\u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c\u201d\uff0c\u4e0d\u4f9d\u8d56\u52a8\u6001\u751f\u6210\u5b57\u5178\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64 `expert_topk` \u5c5e\u4e8e\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u5148\u7b5b\u6e05\u695a\uff1a`expert_topk` \u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\uff1b`lowrank_expert_topk`\u3001`lowrank_expert_residual`\u3001`two_stage_residual_expert`\u3001`factorized_expert_topk` \u5c5e\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9\uff1b`batch_topk`\u3001`adaptive_budget_topk` \u7b49 batch/sample-coupled family \u5c5e\u4e0d\u517c\u5bb9\uff0c\u4e0d\u80fd\u7ee7\u7eed\u9a71\u52a8 frontier\u3002\u76f8\u5bf9 r69 \u4ec5\u628a `NUM_EXPERTS` \u4ece 32 \u63d0\u5230 64\uff0c\u5728\u4fdd\u6301 `ARCHITECTURE=expert_topk`\u3001`K=160`\u3001`EXPANSION_FACTOR=1`\u3001`OPTIMIZER=adam`\u3001`LR=8e-4` \u548c\u5176\u4f59\u8bad\u7ec3\u914d\u65b9\u4e0d\u53d8\u65f6\uff0c\u76f4\u63a5\u56de\u7b54\u5f53\u524d\u4f4e\u6210\u672c\u5e26\u6700\u5173\u952e\u7684 MoE-like \u7ed3\u6784\u95ee\u9898\uff1a\u5982\u679c routed-only family \u5728 0.22x \u5de6\u53f3\u7684\u74f6\u9888\u4ecd\u6709\u4e00\u90e8\u5206\u6765\u81ea\u603b\u9759\u6001\u5b50\u5e93\u5bb9\u91cf\u4e0d\u8db3\uff0c\u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u67e5\u8868\u9884\u7b97\u672c\u8eab\uff0c\u90a3\u4e48\u628a\u603b\u5bb9\u91cf\u7ee7\u7eed\u505a true sparse-capacity \u6269\u5bb9\u3001\u540c\u65f6\u4fdd\u6301 `ACTIVE_EXPERTS=1` \u7684\u77ed\u6fc0\u6d3b\u8def\u5f84\uff0c\u5e94\u80fd\u5728\u51e0\u4e4e\u540c\u4e00 total_cost \u4e0b\u7ee7\u7eed\u538b\u4f4e FVU\uff0c\u5e76\u5f62\u6210\u65b0\u7684\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500 Pareto \u6bb5\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:38:      "`lowrank_expert_topk` \u4e0a\u7684\u5bb9\u91cf\u6269\u5bb9\u8d1f\u7ed3\u679c\u4e0d\u80fd\u76f4\u63a5\u5426\u5b9a routed-only `expert_topk`\uff1b\u4e24\u8005\u74f6\u9888\u4f4d\u7f6e\u4e0d\u540c\uff0c\u672c\u8f6e\u662f\u5bf9\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9 routed-only \u524d\u6cbf\u7684\u72ec\u7acb\u9a8c\u8bc1\u3002"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_expert_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Final reconstruction stays x_hat = sum_{r=1..R} beta_r(x) u_r + sum_{i in S_{e(x-t(x))}(x-t(x))} alpha_{e,i}(x) b_{e,i}, with t(x) = sum_{r=1..R} beta_r(x) u_r. This exports to the LUTurbo/Lottable path as a static trunk table lookup plus a single routed static expert sublibrary lookup plus a finite weighted sum, so `lowrank_expert_topk` is extended-compatible. Compatibility screen before proposing this round: `expert_topk` is directly compatible; `lowrank_expert_topk`, `lowrank_expert_residual`, and `two_stage_residual_expert` are extended-compatible; batch-coupled families such as `batch_topk` and `adaptive_budget_topk` are incompatible and must stay off the active frontier. Relative to r60, changing only `TRUNK_RANK` from 64 to 32 tests the missing mid-trunk point in the low-cost band: if the routed-only improvement from r59 to r60 was not all-or-nothing, this should recover much of r60's FVU while moving left from the current lowrank+expert anchor and potentially create a new compatible Pareto segment between `expert_topk` and `lowrank_expert_residual`.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:20:    "summary": "Use Round 70 for a low-cost structural probe in `lowrank_expert_topk`: start from r60 and only reduce `TRUNK_RANK` to 32. The goal is to map whether shared low-rank trunk width can produce a new compatible Pareto point in the 0.3x-0.5x band, instead of continuing plain-selector K sweeps or more local cleanup on `lowrank_expert_residual`.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:23:    "family_name": "lowrank_expert_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:36:      "`lowrank_expert_topk` now has informative anchors at `TRUNK_RANK=16` and `64` under `K=128, NUM_EXPERTS=32`; `TRUNK_RANK=32` is the clean missing midpoint for the same compatible family.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:41:      "If `TRUNK_RANK=32` falls back close to the routed-only `expert_topk` band, treat that as evidence that `lowrank_expert_topk` has a sharp trunk-width floor and shift low-cost budget back to `lowrank_expert_residual` or pure `expert_topk` rather than more MoE-capacity expansion.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:53:    "architecture": "lowrank_expert_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0070.json:62:    "description": "Use Round 70 for a low-cost structural probe in `lowrank_expert_topk`: start from r60 and only reduce `TRUNK_RANK` to 32. The goal is to map whether shared low-rank trunk width can produce a new compatible Pareto point in the 0.3x-0.5x band, instead of continuing plain-selector K sweeps or more local cleanup on `lowrank_expert_residual`.",
